<TITLE> Bomb blast in Pakistani city; at least 3 dead </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 ISLAMABAD, Feb 25 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A suicide bomber attacked a Pakistani military vehicle on a main road in the city of Rawalpindi on Monday, killing himself and two or three other people, a government and military official said. The blast happened a week after Pakistan held largely peaceful parliamentary elections and was the first bomb attack outside the violence-plagued northwest since the vote. "It was suicide bombing. Three or four people including bomber were killed," said senior city government official Irfan Ellahi. Several major attacks have taken place in Rawalpindi since the middle of last year, including the killing of opposition leader Benazir Bhutto and more than 20 of her supporters in a gun and suicide bomb attack as she left a rally on Dec. 27. Monday's blast was outside an office of the government's national data registration agency, on a crowded main road in the city, which is home to the headquarters of the Pakistani military. "I can see pieces of flesh littering the road and four damaged vehicles," a witness said. Police and troops cordoned off the site of the attack, the witness sa
